WEBVTT

00:00.960 --> 00:01.710
[ Phone ringing ]

00:01.711 --> 00:02.621
Previously on "Slasher".

00:05.548 --> 00:06.628
No!

00:07.425 --> 00:08.540
I can't stay here.

00:08.551 --> 00:10.633
All right, that's it.
Let's hit the road.

00:10.636 --> 00:12.467
-Can I talk to you for a second?
-You're not coming.

00:12.889 --> 00:13.674
[ Screaming ]

00:14.599 --> 00:15.759
This is my fault.

00:16.726 --> 00:19.684
Grandma, what did you do?

00:20.313 --> 00:22.019
GRANDMA:
So I waited on that bridge.

00:22.356 --> 00:24.483
And when they drove by, I...

00:25.485 --> 00:26.691
[ Car crashing ]

00:26.694 --> 00:27.774
[ Screaming ]

00:27.778 --> 00:29.734
You could have died out there.

00:30.573 --> 00:31.983
[ Groaning ]

00:33.201 --> 00:34.316
[ Screaming ]

00:34.785 --> 00:36.070
No! Stop!

00:36.704 --> 00:38.740
SARAH: He could have killed me
multiple times, but he didn't.

00:38.915 --> 00:41.122
I'm safe. I'm not a target.

00:50.801 --> 00:51.756
[ Alarm sounding ]

01:14.075 --> 01:16.441
[ Footsteps approaching ]

01:17.370 --> 01:18.325
[ Knock at the door ]

01:20.748 --> 01:21.954
You awake?

01:23.668 --> 01:24.874
Yeah.

01:30.675 --> 01:31.664
[ Sighs ]

01:31.926 --> 01:34.258
[ Birds chirping ]

01:34.262 --> 01:35.843
I love that photo.

01:37.473 --> 01:39.259
She had such a green thumb.

01:39.809 --> 01:42.050
She could make anything grow.

01:43.771 --> 01:46.262
I think that's where
I'll scatter her ashes...

01:46.649 --> 01:47.684
in her garden.

01:48.109 --> 01:49.645
She'd like that.

01:50.069 --> 01:51.354
I should have been there.

01:51.904 --> 01:54.281
There's nothing you could do.

01:54.824 --> 01:56.655
There was no stopping him.

01:57.910 --> 01:59.741
I'm so sorry.

02:01.247 --> 02:02.612
[ Doorbell ringing ]

02:02.623 --> 02:03.408
[ Sniffs ]

02:04.000 --> 02:07.117
-I'll get it.
-No, no, let me.

02:12.300 --> 02:14.040
Dylan, it's the police!

02:14.635 --> 02:16.171
Well, the truck
was found abandoned.

02:16.345 --> 02:17.255
Not too far

02:17.263 --> 02:18.969
from where your grandmother
was forced off the road.

02:19.140 --> 02:20.425
Who does it belong to?

02:20.891 --> 02:21.971
Trent McBride.

02:24.270 --> 02:25.350
Her nephew?

02:25.563 --> 02:27.269
There's no way
that's a coincidence.

02:28.649 --> 02:30.514
So you're saying
he's The Executioner?

02:30.901 --> 02:34.234
Well, Trent inherited
Verna McBride's entire estate.

02:34.238 --> 02:36.399
And he did have a falling out
with Justin Faysal

02:36.407 --> 02:37.362
over his property.

02:38.034 --> 02:39.899
But my grandmother...?

02:41.162 --> 02:42.242
We're working on that.

02:43.581 --> 02:45.367
We will bring Trent in...

02:45.791 --> 02:47.747
...and we will question him.

02:48.419 --> 02:50.751
This nightmare
might well come to an end.

02:51.881 --> 02:53.371
[Animal groaning ]

02:57.303 --> 02:58.793
[ Birds chirping ]

03:09.815 --> 03:10.770
[ Cracking noise ]

03:17.531 --> 03:18.520
[ Gunshot ]

03:20.076 --> 03:22.909
Aw, come on!
What the hell, asshole?

03:23.287 --> 03:25.198
You didn't see me, right?

03:28.250 --> 03:30.241
Confirm your target
before you take a shot.

03:30.252 --> 03:31.241
That buck's mine!

03:31.671 --> 03:32.535
[ Gunshot ]

03:33.881 --> 03:37.920
[ Gunshots continue ]

03:53.776 --> 03:56.643
This is done! You hear me?!

03:57.988 --> 03:58.818
Done!

03:59.240 --> 04:00.195
I'm not movin', and I...

04:00.366 --> 04:02.197
[ Gunshots ]

04:10.251 --> 04:11.616
[ Screaming ]

04:14.380 --> 04:15.460
Oh, no, shit.

04:15.756 --> 04:18.372
[ Screaming continues ]

04:18.592 --> 04:20.173
Oh, shit.

04:22.096 --> 04:23.461
[ Birds singing ]

04:23.723 --> 04:25.679
TRENT: Hey, help... help me.

04:25.975 --> 04:27.886
Help me, please. Hey!

04:28.144 --> 04:30.055
Oh, God!
What do you want!?

04:30.271 --> 04:31.602
[ Screaming and panting ]

04:31.605 --> 04:32.469
What's that?

04:32.732 --> 04:35.018
Oh, no! What are you...?

04:35.317 --> 04:37.353
What are you doing?

04:37.361 --> 04:38.476
No! No, no, no.

04:38.487 --> 04:40.068
[ Screaming ]

04:40.281 --> 04:41.270
[ Snake hissing ]

04:41.449 --> 04:43.235
TRENT:
No! No, no, no. Don't!

04:43.617 --> 04:45.448
DonTlNo!

04:45.453 --> 04:46.408
[ Trent groaning ]

04:46.787 --> 04:49.199
[ Trent screaming ]

05:04.180 --> 05:07.343
[ Screaming continues ]

05:16.859 --> 05:19.271
[ Police sirens ]

05:26.994 --> 05:28.985
Side door... we're going in.

05:31.123 --> 05:32.408
Come on. Come on.

05:33.959 --> 05:35.995
[ Birds chirping ]

05:40.466 --> 05:43.048
CAM: Trent McBride,
if you're in here, come out!

05:43.469 --> 05:44.959
Hands where we can see 'em!

05:46.555 --> 05:47.340
Trent?

05:47.932 --> 05:49.172
OFFICER: Clear!

05:52.770 --> 05:54.180
McBride residence, clear.

05:54.188 --> 05:55.803
-Let's sweep the area.
-FEMALE OFFICER: Copy that.

05:55.981 --> 05:57.187
Get the dog.

05:58.901 --> 05:59.936
[ Dog barking ]

06:08.577 --> 06:09.407
Whoa.

06:10.955 --> 06:11.910
Hold up. Hold up.

06:12.122 --> 06:13.202
[ Dog whining ]

06:15.501 --> 06:16.661
Trent McBride!

06:17.878 --> 06:20.415
This is Officer Cam Henry,
Waterbury Police.

06:21.257 --> 06:23.543
I am armed, so stand down.

06:31.433 --> 06:33.014
[ Snakes hissing ]

06:47.032 --> 06:48.943
[ Phone ringing ]

06:52.204 --> 06:53.910
CHIEF: All right,
so here's the update.

06:54.665 --> 06:56.951
We traced the truck
back to Trent McBride,

06:56.959 --> 06:58.620
but when my guys
got there to question him...

06:59.587 --> 07:01.578
...they found him dead.

07:04.550 --> 07:06.336
That's a pit of snakes.

07:07.553 --> 07:09.043
Brought in a herpetologist.

07:09.555 --> 07:11.261
She identified a bunch
of different species.

07:11.682 --> 07:13.092
Four of them venomous.

07:13.100 --> 07:15.591
The others just common snakes,
like garter snakes.

07:15.603 --> 07:17.468
There's a nasty little thing
called a Blue Racer.

07:19.815 --> 07:22.101
Then there's this guy.

07:22.526 --> 07:23.811
The eastern brown snake.

07:23.819 --> 07:26.026
CHIEF: All the way
from Australia.

07:26.030 --> 07:27.691
Second deadliest snake
in the world,

07:27.698 --> 07:29.484
right behind the inland taipan.

07:30.117 --> 07:32.108
My expert believes
it is the snake responsible

07:32.119 --> 07:34.075
for the bite
that killed Trent McBride.

07:34.288 --> 07:35.903
I don't get it.
Why snakes?

07:35.915 --> 07:36.950
With sloth, you're thrown in...

07:36.957 --> 07:38.538
Because the pit
is punishment.

07:40.794 --> 07:43.171
Goes back
to the seven deadly sins.

07:43.172 --> 07:45.458
Punishment for sloth is being
thrown into a pit of vipers.

07:45.466 --> 07:46.546
Did I get that right, Sarah?

07:47.885 --> 07:49.876
So Trent's not The Executioner?

07:50.429 --> 07:52.090
And he's a victim.

07:52.097 --> 07:52.847
CHIEF:
Looks that way.

07:53.349 --> 07:56.011
With sloth...
It doesn't make sense.

07:57.144 --> 07:59.726
Trent McBride is the last person
I'd call lazy.

08:00.064 --> 08:01.679
I mean,
he was June's partner for years.

08:01.690 --> 08:02.975
He was a paramedic, he...

08:02.983 --> 08:04.939
He competed
in a bunch of Iron Mans.

08:04.944 --> 08:07.060
That's why we gotta look
into this guy's past.

08:07.071 --> 08:09.278
See if he's got any skeletons
hanging in his closet.

08:10.157 --> 08:12.022
So you're back to square one.

08:12.034 --> 08:14.821
-How many times is that now?
-Look, I get it, Sarah.

08:15.371 --> 08:18.329
You don't like me.
You think I suck at my job.

08:19.249 --> 08:20.830
Well, lucky for me...

08:21.001 --> 08:22.161
I don't give a shit.

08:23.379 --> 08:24.664
You have yourself
a nice day now.

08:24.838 --> 08:26.544
Okay, come on.

08:29.468 --> 08:30.583
[ Door opening ]

08:34.264 --> 08:35.174
[ Door closing ]

08:35.182 --> 08:39.141
Now I hate him. He is
ineffectual, incompetent, rude.

08:39.144 --> 08:41.726
Yeah, well, he's a cop, love.
That's how they are.

08:41.730 --> 08:42.560
Cam's not.

08:42.773 --> 08:44.889
Cam is not in charge.
Vaughn is.

08:44.900 --> 08:47.061
So what's the use of butting
heads with him, you know?

08:47.403 --> 08:49.189
Y'know, Tom Winston's
made more breaks in this case

08:49.196 --> 08:50.436
than Chief Vaughn.

08:51.991 --> 08:54.152
Maybe it's time for Tom...

08:54.326 --> 08:56.942
...to speak to the residents
of Waterbury directly?

08:57.204 --> 08:58.284
Okay, right, Dylan.

08:58.288 --> 09:00.904
I need you to be my husband
right now, not a journalist.

09:00.916 --> 09:03.077
I'm speaking to you
as your husband.

09:03.544 --> 09:05.250
Are you kidding?

09:05.254 --> 09:07.040
That be like giving Charles
Manson his own talk show.

09:07.506 --> 09:09.121
Then, you take it.

09:09.675 --> 09:11.631
Seriously, let me interview you.

09:11.635 --> 09:13.796
Somebody's going to do the story
on you eventually, right?

09:14.263 --> 09:16.504
-So why not you?
-Your husband.

09:16.765 --> 09:18.175
Someone you trust.

09:20.602 --> 09:22.558
-And I can talk about anything?
-Anything.

09:22.813 --> 09:24.303
No holds barred.

09:33.782 --> 09:34.942
You ready?

09:39.455 --> 09:42.743
Your parents were murdered by
Tom Winston nearly 30 years ago.

09:43.250 --> 09:46.913
And recently your grandmother...
succumbed to the same fate.

09:46.920 --> 09:48.376
If you could look
The Executioner in his eye...

09:48.380 --> 09:50.666
No, no, I think you mean
if I could look him in the mask.

09:52.176 --> 09:54.633
He's too much of a coward
to show his face.

09:55.679 --> 09:57.419
What would you say?

09:59.808 --> 10:01.309
I would say...

10:03.187 --> 10:05.269
I would say that Brenda Merritt
did a terrible thing,

10:05.272 --> 10:07.604
and my grandmother
deserved to be punished.

10:08.400 --> 10:10.186
But you took the law
into your own hands

10:10.194 --> 10:11.809
and on whose authority?

10:12.196 --> 10:16.064
And I... I think he'd probably
say, "God's authority."

10:16.075 --> 10:18.157
Wow, I'm not really religious,

10:18.160 --> 10:21.903
but I think the Bible's pretty
clear, "Thou shalt not kill."

10:23.749 --> 10:25.239
-You're angry?
-Yeah.

10:25.250 --> 10:26.956
Of course, I'm angry.

10:26.960 --> 10:30.293
And I'm sad. And I'm upset.
But I'm not afraid.

10:30.297 --> 10:31.412
No?

10:33.050 --> 10:34.790
When something
like this happens...

10:34.802 --> 10:36.008
You know,
at first, you're numb.

10:36.011 --> 10:37.342
Hmm.

10:37.346 --> 10:38.802
And then
when you start to be able

10:38.806 --> 10:40.171
to wrap your mind around it,

10:40.182 --> 10:44.221
your imagination can take you
to some pretty dark places.

10:45.479 --> 10:47.219
You think about
what your loved ones

10:47.231 --> 10:48.687
went through before they died.

10:49.983 --> 10:51.598
About how terrified they were.

10:52.486 --> 10:53.851
About how much they suffered.

10:56.323 --> 10:58.234
And then you find the pain.

10:58.826 --> 11:00.407
And the rage.

11:01.328 --> 11:03.239
And you want revenge.

11:05.749 --> 11:09.412
I despise The Executioner's
actions, but I don't hate him.

11:09.878 --> 11:12.255
Because hate is just fear,
and I am not afraid.

11:13.674 --> 11:15.756
The Executioner is afraid.

11:16.301 --> 11:18.132
He '5 a coward.

11:18.137 --> 11:20.048
Him, Tom Winston,

11:20.055 --> 11:22.922
anyone who's ever taken
the life of another person.

11:24.059 --> 11:25.469
Co wards.

11:26.228 --> 11:28.970
I'm a coward.
I'm a coward?

11:28.981 --> 11:31.472
I'm a coward!
Tom Winston is a coward?!

11:31.483 --> 11:34.725
How dare you!
How dare you!

11:34.987 --> 11:35.851
How dare you!

11:36.738 --> 11:41.903
[Yelling ]

11:43.787 --> 11:45.027
Pain!

11:45.330 --> 11:46.945
I'm the coward?!

11:53.755 --> 11:55.791
So let's, uh, bury the water
symposium story

11:55.799 --> 11:57.414
as far back in the paper
as possible.

11:57.426 --> 11:58.962
It's an important issue up here.

11:59.178 --> 12:01.169
Psycho killer's stalking
our town's citizens...

12:01.889 --> 12:03.925
Shoreline water erosion.

12:04.433 --> 12:07.470
We have a little bit
of a toss up, right?

12:07.477 --> 12:10.184
Okay, there is a hole
in page 5.

12:11.231 --> 12:13.938
The A-frame pulled
their one-quarter vertical.

12:13.942 --> 12:15.933
We can put
the water story there.

12:16.236 --> 12:18.693
And that's tomorrow's paper.
Thank you, everyone.

12:19.072 --> 12:20.198
Not enough tourists

12:20.199 --> 12:21.780
ordering the onion and liver
poutine, are they, eh?

12:21.992 --> 12:24.404
Oh, less business for them
means less business for us.

12:24.411 --> 12:26.493
Thank God, we're selling
like hotcakes right now.

12:26.496 --> 12:28.987
All this talk of breakfast
is making me hungry.

12:29.833 --> 12:30.822
Forget breakfast.

12:31.543 --> 12:33.124
What are you doing for dinner?

12:33.128 --> 12:35.039
No plans. Why?

12:35.547 --> 12:38.129
Because you're gonna have dinner
with me tonight.

12:38.508 --> 12:39.839
Me and Lisa-Ann Follows.

12:41.094 --> 12:43.506
-The Lisa-Ann Follows?
-Mm-hm.

12:43.931 --> 12:45.091
She's flying up from New York

12:45.098 --> 12:46.929
to cover the murders
and some local experts.

12:46.934 --> 12:48.549
And dinner is our audition.

12:48.894 --> 12:50.759
[ Phone ringing ]

12:50.938 --> 12:52.849
You should maybe wear
something tighter.

12:53.273 --> 12:54.058
Tight.

12:55.234 --> 12:57.145
I... I can do tight.

12:57.319 --> 12:59.401
Yeah, no, tight's good.

13:01.990 --> 13:04.367
[ Cell phone ringing ]

13:08.288 --> 13:09.243
Hello?

13:09.248 --> 13:11.489
OPERA TOR: Sarah Bennett,
you have a call from...

13:11.500 --> 13:12.535
TOM: Tom Winston.

13:12.542 --> 13:14.407
OPERATOR:
Press one to accept.

13:19.174 --> 13:20.163
TOM: Hello, Sarah.

13:20.968 --> 13:22.583
SARAH: What do you want
to tell me?

13:23.345 --> 13:25.336
I read your article
in The Bulletin.

13:25.347 --> 13:26.382
Okay.

13:26.598 --> 13:27.804
Yeah.

13:28.350 --> 13:30.090
Is that what you really think?

13:30.102 --> 13:32.013
About The Executioner?
He's a coward?

13:32.396 --> 13:34.637
I wouldn't have said it
if I didn't mean it.

13:34.648 --> 13:36.889
The Executioner doesn't think
like you do.

13:37.359 --> 13:41.102
You can't... shame him.
You can't... reason with him.

13:41.113 --> 13:44.150
All you can do is fuel him
and his obsession.

13:44.408 --> 13:46.114
Yeah, you'd know this how, huh?

13:47.202 --> 13:49.784
I was obsessed
with your parents.

13:51.999 --> 13:53.990
I know you think
he can 't hurt you,

13:54.251 --> 13:55.536
but the last thing
you wanna do

13:55.544 --> 13:57.080
is make that a challenge
for him.

13:58.046 --> 13:59.911
Okay, I'm hearing you.

13:59.923 --> 14:01.424
Good.

14:02.968 --> 14:03.798
Tom?

14:05.345 --> 14:06.425
Yes?

14:08.307 --> 14:11.174
You wouldn't ever consider
talking to my husband,

14:11.601 --> 14:13.683
would you, for The Bulletin?

14:17.065 --> 14:19.181
Is this something
you want me to do?

14:19.693 --> 14:21.433
Simple yes or no.

14:22.362 --> 14:24.023
TOM: On one condition.

14:24.614 --> 14:26.354
Well, he can't pay you.

14:26.616 --> 14:28.447
I'd like a memento.

14:31.163 --> 14:32.653
What kind of memento?

14:33.373 --> 14:35.079
A lock of your hair.

14:37.044 --> 14:38.705
Forget I asked.

14:50.390 --> 14:51.846
You know, if Trent
was The Executioner,

14:51.850 --> 14:52.635
that would make sense.

14:52.893 --> 14:53.632
[ Shivers ]

14:53.894 --> 14:56.055
That boy was seriously
disturbed.

14:56.646 --> 14:59.262
Norman Bates
meets the Unabomber.

14:59.649 --> 15:01.435
I still figure it could be
Heather Peterson.

15:01.902 --> 15:04.188
Yeah, but it wasn't so,
who could it be?

15:04.196 --> 15:06.187
In this town?

15:06.490 --> 15:08.071
I think we'll be here
till next week.

15:08.784 --> 15:10.399
Well, let's start
with who it isn't.

15:11.119 --> 15:12.655
You, me, obviously.

15:12.662 --> 15:13.788
Anyone who was at your party

15:13.789 --> 15:15.745
the night Verna McBride
was killed.

15:15.749 --> 15:17.831
Well, it's not
my little guardian angel

15:17.834 --> 15:19.449
who saved my life.

15:20.420 --> 15:21.796
It's obviously not Dylan.

15:21.797 --> 15:23.958
He was with you the night
Verna got sliced and diced.

15:26.510 --> 15:28.125
No, no, he wasn't actually.

15:28.136 --> 15:30.593
He... he had to go back
into work.

15:32.349 --> 15:35.261
This is your husband
we're talking about?

15:35.268 --> 15:37.759
And he's not even from here.

15:38.230 --> 15:41.688
His only tie to Waterbury
is you. Is there a motive?

15:44.611 --> 15:46.522
Chief Vaughn.

15:47.114 --> 15:49.230
Well, he's either
a complete idiot or a suspect.

15:49.241 --> 15:50.651
So I'm gonna say both.

15:52.911 --> 15:54.572
-Cam?
-No.

15:54.996 --> 15:57.908
No, Cam is innocent. I mean,
I don't have any proof, but...

15:57.916 --> 16:02.751
So he could go either way?
Like me in university.

16:04.047 --> 16:05.912
Uh... June?

16:06.633 --> 16:07.964
She was Trent's partner.

16:08.135 --> 16:09.215
You really think June
would come up

16:09.219 --> 16:10.254
with something this complicated?

16:10.262 --> 16:11.172
Rawr.

16:11.513 --> 16:13.799
Enough, okay.
That wasn't very nice.

16:13.807 --> 16:15.638
-I like June, I do.
-I know.

16:15.642 --> 16:17.007
-She's pretty.
-She's pretty.

16:17.394 --> 16:18.975
She's sweet and...

16:19.521 --> 16:21.603
I'm not making this
any better, am I?

16:22.441 --> 16:23.931
-Okay, I'm gonna stop.
-Okay.

16:24.943 --> 16:26.558
-Moving on.
-Yeah.

16:29.614 --> 16:31.024
Tom Winston.

16:32.033 --> 16:34.615
Well, he's crazy enough,
but he's behind bars.

16:34.619 --> 16:37.611
So what?
Serial killers have groupies.

16:39.374 --> 16:40.784
What if Tom is the brains,

16:40.792 --> 16:42.828
and he's got someone
on the outside being the brawn?

16:43.128 --> 16:46.495
Yeah, but he doesn't see anyone.
I mean, except for me.

16:48.175 --> 16:50.131
Yes, he does.

16:50.343 --> 16:52.174
Alan Henry.

16:53.054 --> 16:55.386
-Alan's his religious counselor?
-Uh-huh.

16:55.390 --> 16:57.972
And these are religious murders,
right?

16:59.644 --> 17:00.895
No, wait,
that doesn't make sense.

17:00.896 --> 17:03.308
No, Tom tried to kill Alan.

17:03.315 --> 17:06.478
No, he actually didn't.
Tom spared him. He told me.

17:12.449 --> 17:14.189
Oh, shit.

17:18.330 --> 17:20.491
[ Phone ringing ]

17:20.999 --> 17:23.706
CHIEF: Tell me about your
relationship with Trent McBride.

17:24.419 --> 17:25.704
We were co-workers.

17:25.712 --> 17:27.748
CHIEF: How long
did you work together for?

17:27.756 --> 17:30.839
A few years.
Three years and a bit.

17:31.092 --> 17:33.048
CHIEF: Did he have
any romantic relationships

17:33.053 --> 17:34.133
that you knew about?

17:34.137 --> 17:36.970
I... I don't know. I haven't
talked to Trent for a while.

17:37.224 --> 17:39.055
What about back then?

17:39.726 --> 17:41.762
He liked women.

17:42.145 --> 17:43.726
I don't know any specifics
beyond that.

17:44.648 --> 17:46.730
Did Trent have a temper, June?

17:47.734 --> 17:51.477
Trent's... bark
was worse than his bite.

17:52.906 --> 17:54.487
He was a good guy.

17:55.033 --> 17:56.534
Great worker, always on time --

17:56.535 --> 17:58.776
I'm not looking
for a job reference here.

17:59.788 --> 18:01.653
I wanna know
what this guy's interests were,

18:01.665 --> 18:03.826
what his hobbies were,
what he did with his free time.

18:04.000 --> 18:06.491
He liked to hunt and go camping.
You know all this.

18:06.503 --> 18:08.459
Did you know about his interest
in taxidermy?

18:08.672 --> 18:10.583
-Sewing up dead animals.
-I know what taxidermy is.

18:11.508 --> 18:12.293
No.

18:12.467 --> 18:14.503
Did he ever mention or talk
about The Executioner?

18:14.761 --> 18:15.671
No.

18:15.679 --> 18:17.590
I feel like you're trying to get
me to say something about Trent

18:17.597 --> 18:18.586
that wasn't true.

18:18.932 --> 18:21.799
Trent was a stand-up guy.
He didn't deserve to die.

18:25.814 --> 18:28.351
June, we're asking everyone
who knew Trent McBride

18:28.358 --> 18:29.894
these questions.

18:30.569 --> 18:32.810
He was hunted down and killed.

18:34.197 --> 18:35.232
Okay.

18:35.574 --> 18:38.316
Now, when he left, did he leave
on good terms or bad terms?

18:38.326 --> 18:39.862
Any employees,
were they enemies?

18:39.869 --> 18:43.111
Any family members or patients
that might've had a grudge?

18:51.131 --> 18:53.213
-Is everything okay?
-Deputy Henry!

18:53.216 --> 18:54.456
Yeah, I'm fine.

18:56.011 --> 18:58.377
All right, why don't you
head home?

18:58.388 --> 18:59.924
I'll see you in a bit.

18:59.931 --> 19:01.637
[ Phone ringing ]

19:02.684 --> 19:04.424
Beautiful day, huh?

19:16.114 --> 19:17.354
[ Sighs ]

19:23.204 --> 19:24.660
[ Continues to sigh ]

19:25.582 --> 19:27.538
[ Crickets chirping ]

19:31.296 --> 19:33.753
Right, say it was Alan Henry.

19:34.799 --> 19:36.335
I mean, why'd he go around
killing people?

19:36.551 --> 19:38.633
His son's a cop, he doesn't even
have to call 911.

19:39.012 --> 19:40.877
Have you ever read
the Old Testament?

19:41.056 --> 19:42.512
God is one angry father.

19:42.515 --> 19:44.551
Commanding His followers

19:44.559 --> 19:47.596
to spill oceans
of nonbeliever blood.

19:47.812 --> 19:50.019
Trust me, Sunday school
was darkside as shit.

19:50.023 --> 19:51.263
JUNE: You can't cut me off.

19:51.274 --> 19:52.480
I'll tell you
when I've had enough!

19:52.817 --> 19:54.102
Asshole!

19:57.197 --> 19:58.903
Hey! June!

19:58.907 --> 20:00.818
Maybe, wait up a sec, huh?

20:01.618 --> 20:02.448
SARAH: June?

20:02.869 --> 20:05.781
Hey, hey, June.
Um, honey?

20:06.081 --> 20:07.287
Sweetie. Sweetie. Hey!

20:07.999 --> 20:10.115
-Hi!
-Hey!

20:10.377 --> 20:12.993
Oh, what are you guys
doing here?

20:13.254 --> 20:15.085
It is so good to see you.

20:15.090 --> 20:17.297
You're... you're not going home
already, are you?

20:17.550 --> 20:19.757
Well, I don't want to,
but those bastards in there...

20:19.761 --> 20:22.002
I mean, all I wanted to do was
have a drink in honor of Trent.

20:22.222 --> 20:24.008
Hey, why don't you hang out with
us tonight?

20:24.015 --> 20:25.346
SARAH: Yeah, yeah.

20:25.350 --> 20:27.762
-SARAH: Yeah.
-You guys got anything to drink?

20:28.770 --> 20:30.055
JUNE: You got any tequila.

20:30.063 --> 20:32.770
I'll keep these keys here.

20:32.774 --> 20:34.105
June, that's a little too close
to the water.

20:34.109 --> 20:34.768
Whoa! June! June!

20:34.984 --> 20:37.270
-What? Noll.
-June, be careful. Be care...

20:37.278 --> 20:38.734
-Oh! June what are you doing?
-June!

20:38.738 --> 20:40.239
Going for a swim.
You should come.

20:40.615 --> 20:43.277
I forgot my Speedo at home,
babe. Uh...

20:43.493 --> 20:44.403
You don't need a bathing suit.

20:44.411 --> 20:45.571
—Oh!
-You wanna...

20:45.578 --> 20:46.328
Oh, wow!

20:49.082 --> 20:50.492
Come on, Robin.

20:51.876 --> 20:53.662
It's not like I haven't seen you
naked before.

20:53.878 --> 20:55.493
Remember? Ken Simon's pool?

20:55.505 --> 20:56.995
Okay.

20:57.006 --> 20:57.870
JUNE: We all went
skinny dipping.

20:57.882 --> 21:00.339
-You keep an eye on her.
-...at her parents' hot tub.

21:00.510 --> 21:01.920
-[ June laughing ]
-ROBIN: Yeah, she'll be fine.

21:01.928 --> 21:04.135
She's got built-in
life preservers.

21:04.139 --> 21:05.299
Okay, come on, sweetie.

21:05.640 --> 21:07.972
Let's get out of there.
Come on!

21:09.144 --> 21:11.601
Cam. Hey, um, it's Sarah.

21:12.105 --> 21:15.472
Yeah, I'm at the A-frame,
and June...

21:17.110 --> 21:18.896
June's gonna be right home.

21:19.988 --> 21:21.194
I was living in LA.

21:21.197 --> 21:23.313
when the "Grim Sleeper"
was killing black women.

21:23.491 --> 21:28.827
I've had mass murderers,
wife killers, terrorists,

21:29.038 --> 21:32.656
kidnappers, you name it,
dregs of society on my show.

21:32.667 --> 21:34.453
Takes a lot to shake me.

21:34.461 --> 21:37.999
These killings...
scare the shit out of me.

21:38.006 --> 21:39.746
I know exactly
what you're saying.

21:39.758 --> 21:41.623
When the original murders
took place...

21:41.885 --> 21:43.921
Your wife's parents
were the victims?

21:44.512 --> 21:47.470
-Yeah, yeah they were.
-FOLLOWS: I can't even imagine.

21:47.640 --> 21:48.629
Oh, it was terrible.

21:48.641 --> 21:52.509
Actually, I can, because you did
such an incredible job,

21:52.687 --> 21:54.678
telling Sarah's story,
all of these stories,

21:54.689 --> 21:55.804
bringing them to life.

21:55.815 --> 21:57.225
Thank you.

21:57.233 --> 21:59.224
Uh, you know,
with material like this,

21:59.235 --> 22:01.021
it kind of writes itself.

22:01.029 --> 22:03.395
Okay... Dylan.

22:03.782 --> 22:06.194
If this is gonna work,
you need to drop all of that,

22:06.201 --> 22:10.194
"Gee golly, aw shucks"
polite crap.

22:10.205 --> 22:12.947
I'll eat you up and spit you out
like a bad piece of sushi.

22:12.957 --> 22:14.913
You want that?
You don't want that.

22:18.838 --> 22:22.831
These murders have terrorized
this community.

22:23.051 --> 22:27.090
The Executioner has acted
like judge, jury, and hangman.

22:27.096 --> 22:30.133
If we don't give a voice
to these people, who will?

22:30.725 --> 22:32.306
We owe it to them.

22:37.065 --> 22:39.852
Kinda like that
or is that too much?

22:40.109 --> 22:41.360
What do you think?

22:42.654 --> 22:44.485
Do that tomorrow,
and you're gold.

22:44.739 --> 22:46.946
[ Laughing ] Now,
this original Executioner,

22:46.950 --> 22:49.487
the one rotting in jail,
have you met him?

22:49.494 --> 22:50.904
I... No, I have not.

22:50.912 --> 22:51.947
I think you should try
to book him.

22:52.121 --> 22:53.702
-Yeah?
-It's ratings dynamite.

22:54.332 --> 22:56.323
Robin, get in here!

22:56.668 --> 22:59.876
I know you like dudes,
but I promise I won't bite.

23:00.421 --> 23:02.628
If you love me, you’ll swim with me.

23:02.841 --> 23:04.456
I can’t get my arms wet.

23:04.676 --> 23:07.292
Now, you're just making up excuses.

23:11.266 --> 23:13.473
Shit, why is he here?

23:13.852 --> 23:16.889
Come on.
That's a good girl.

23:17.981 --> 23:19.096
Cam...

23:20.275 --> 23:21.515
Listen, don't be upset.

23:21.526 --> 23:23.687
She's just taking Trent's murder
really hard, okay?

23:23.862 --> 23:25.602
June, come on, its time to go home.

23:26.114 --> 23:26.978
All right.

23:27.615 --> 23:28.946
What are you doing here?

23:28.950 --> 23:30.611
Cam's just come to take you
home, you know?

23:31.077 --> 23:34.444
You get there, you have a hot
shower, and you know...

23:35.290 --> 23:37.497
Home and warm, and have a...

23:38.209 --> 23:40.120
You're telling me
what my husband's gonna do?

23:40.128 --> 23:41.618
What?
You speak for him now?

23:42.881 --> 23:44.837
No, I'm sick of it!

23:44.841 --> 23:47.583
Ever since she came here,
she's been like, like a stalker.

23:47.927 --> 23:50.669
Going for walks together,
having private conversations.

23:50.680 --> 23:51.795
Hugging each other!

23:51.806 --> 23:53.762
June, Cam and I
are just friends.

23:53.766 --> 23:55.097
You want Cam,
and you always have!

23:55.101 --> 23:56.511
June, I'm married, so...

23:56.519 --> 23:57.850
That didn't stop
your slut of a mom.

23:57.854 --> 23:59.640
Hey, June, that's enough.

24:01.316 --> 24:02.556
I'm so sorry.

24:03.401 --> 24:05.642
[ Crickets chirping ]

24:10.491 --> 24:12.482
I'm attracted to this story
for a bunch of reasons.

24:12.493 --> 24:14.029
One, it's great drama.

24:14.037 --> 24:16.323
Who doesn't love a series
of murders in a small town?

24:16.331 --> 24:19.198
Two, it's got an incredible
back story.

24:19.417 --> 24:21.203
And it's happening in real time.

24:21.628 --> 24:24.370
Three, it's not on the radar.
Not yet.

24:24.923 --> 24:27.665
That's why I wanted
to be here first.

24:27.675 --> 24:30.257
Trust me, I'm not in Waterbury
for the fine dining.

24:30.428 --> 24:31.213
[ Laughing ]

24:31.429 --> 24:32.179
Right.

24:32.639 --> 24:36.052
Well, Lisa-Ann, I speak
for Dylan, but we are thrilled.

24:36.059 --> 24:37.845
Yeah, and we're
print journalists, so...

24:38.102 --> 24:40.058
-...the opportunity.
- I started as a lawyer.

24:40.063 --> 24:42.805
And you... got a face for T.V.

24:52.784 --> 24:54.194
Oh, no, no, no.
I'll get that.

24:54.202 --> 24:55.908
No, no, please.
You are our guest.

24:55.912 --> 24:58.779
Now, I will go settle the bill.

24:58.998 --> 25:02.536
And then, um, we'll take you
back to your B&B.

25:03.002 --> 25:04.333
Which is very exciting to say.

25:04.587 --> 25:05.997
Isn't it?

25:06.005 --> 25:07.870
Um, we'll, uh, meet you outside.

25:14.097 --> 25:16.588
You're in the majors now,
rookie.

25:17.141 --> 25:18.347
You ready?

25:18.559 --> 25:20.299
Ready as I can be, I guess.

25:20.645 --> 25:21.555
Well, here's the thing, Dylan.

25:21.562 --> 25:24.850
Every story, even as big as this,
has a finite lifespan.

25:24.857 --> 25:28.349
So what are you gonna do when
The Executioner gets eclipsed

25:28.861 --> 25:31.193
by the next young mom
who drowns her eight kids,

25:31.197 --> 25:33.654
or a cosmetic surgeon who
murders his wife with Botox?

25:33.658 --> 25:35.239
Hmm?

25:35.493 --> 25:37.233
Well, I guess I really
haven't thought about...

25:37.245 --> 25:38.530
You should.

25:38.538 --> 25:39.948
Yeah, well, I guess
that's a conversation

25:39.956 --> 25:41.116
you, Alison, and I can have.

25:41.582 --> 25:43.163
Hmm, I’m having it with you.

25:44.836 --> 25:46.542
Well, then, let's talk.

25:48.214 --> 25:49.374
SARAH: I thought
writing was your thing.

25:49.799 --> 25:51.915
It is my thing, darling,
but it's a dying thing.

25:51.926 --> 25:52.836
You don't want me to do it?

25:52.844 --> 25:54.129
SARAH: No, I'm just surprised,
you know.

25:54.137 --> 25:55.968
It's T.V.
It's a big shift.

25:55.972 --> 25:57.963
Yeah, but it's still journalism.

25:59.308 --> 26:01.139
You don't have to watch
if it's gonna make you weird.

26:01.394 --> 26:03.476
Of course,
I'm gonna watch, and...

26:04.647 --> 26:05.762
Do you have to wear makeup?

26:06.065 --> 26:08.181
-You'd like that, wouldn't you?
-Mm-hm.

26:08.693 --> 26:10.684
[ Birds chirping ]

26:11.029 --> 26:12.769
So I spoke to Tom Winston.

26:19.704 --> 26:21.410
And what did he have to say?

26:21.789 --> 26:23.404
He said he'd do it.

26:23.833 --> 26:26.074
-Huh.
-For a lock of my hair.

26:27.628 --> 26:28.617
-That's creepy.
-Yeah.

26:28.629 --> 26:30.130
Wow.

26:30.131 --> 26:30.995
For what?

26:31.007 --> 26:32.668
I don't know,
and I don't wanna know.

26:33.009 --> 26:34.215
God.

26:34.761 --> 26:37.093
I'm sorry I even
asked you to do that.

26:41.476 --> 26:43.341
You know, I'm gonna
make some coffee.

26:43.352 --> 26:44.933
-You want one?
-No, I'm good. I'm good.

26:44.937 --> 26:46.393
Thanks anyway.

26:48.357 --> 26:51.224
[ Birds chirping ]

26:51.569 --> 26:53.070
SARAH: What about some
breakfast? You want cereal?

26:53.071 --> 26:54.982
No, I'm fine, honey.
Thank you.

27:17.512 --> 27:20.925
[ Website playing church music ]

27:22.600 --> 27:24.966
[ Typing ]

27:33.861 --> 27:35.271
[ Door bell rings ]

27:38.908 --> 27:40.398
Hi.

27:41.202 --> 27:42.817
Can we talk?

27:43.788 --> 27:44.994
Yeah.

27:51.963 --> 27:54.124
I only remember snippets.

27:54.423 --> 27:56.254
I get like that
when I drink hard alcohol.

27:56.884 --> 27:59.296
So I stick to wine or cider.

27:59.887 --> 28:01.673
Not that I'm trying
to find an excuse.

28:01.889 --> 28:03.971
'Cause I really am sorry, Sarah.

28:06.060 --> 28:08.676
And I'm...
I'm sorry about Trent.

28:10.940 --> 28:12.896
You two worked together?

28:13.192 --> 28:14.477
Yeah.

28:14.485 --> 28:15.986
We were partners.

28:16.821 --> 28:18.527
Drove the same ambulance.

28:18.531 --> 28:19.771
[ Sighs ]

28:20.700 --> 28:22.486
A lot of late nights,
like one of those things,

28:24.662 --> 28:26.027
[ Sniffling ]

28:26.038 --> 28:27.164
God, what is wrong with me?

28:27.331 --> 28:29.367
No, it's okay, June.

28:30.376 --> 28:31.536
[ Sniffs ]

28:31.794 --> 28:34.035
Anyway, I came here
to apologize.

28:34.547 --> 28:36.879
I was a crazy woman last night.

28:37.466 --> 28:38.797
That wasn't me.

28:40.052 --> 28:41.007
I should go.

28:43.097 --> 28:44.553
June.

28:47.101 --> 28:49.558
Was Trent more
than just a friend from work?

28:50.521 --> 28:51.727
No.

28:53.191 --> 28:54.522
Okay.

28:55.318 --> 28:57.900
I'm upset because he was
murdered. That's normal.

28:59.447 --> 29:00.653
It is. You're right.

29:01.032 --> 29:02.488
I'm sorry.

29:07.038 --> 29:09.450
[ Sobbing ]

29:14.754 --> 29:15.834
Does Cam know?

29:16.964 --> 29:18.215
[ Sniffs ]

29:20.134 --> 29:22.250
We ended it years ago.

29:22.887 --> 29:25.299
Me and Trent...
And I love Cam.

29:25.473 --> 29:27.384
We went to counseling
and worked it all out.

29:27.391 --> 29:29.643
Trent even quit
because of all of it.

29:29.644 --> 29:30.508
But-II

29:31.062 --> 29:32.848
But you still cared for him.

29:34.482 --> 29:36.222
Oh, June, it's okay.

29:36.484 --> 29:38.145
No, I can't mourn.

29:38.152 --> 29:40.108
I can't act sad because
then Cam might think

29:40.112 --> 29:41.568
that we were still...

29:42.573 --> 29:44.074
but we were...

29:44.533 --> 29:45.864
...honest.

29:46.410 --> 29:50.073
-I mean, you can't tell anyone.
-No. No, I promise I won't.

29:51.123 --> 29:53.250
June, I'm sure Cam has told you,

29:53.251 --> 29:56.243
but this killer is targeting
his victims.

29:57.880 --> 29:59.336
Is there anything
in Trent's past?

29:59.340 --> 30:00.796
Something he might have done?

30:02.385 --> 30:04.296
People will hate him.

30:04.762 --> 30:06.423
That can't hurt him now.

30:07.640 --> 30:10.177
But if you know something,
you've gotta speak up.

30:10.643 --> 30:13.100
[ Birds chirping ]

30:14.981 --> 30:16.266
[ Sighs ]

30:17.525 --> 30:19.061
JUNE: It was five years ago.

30:21.070 --> 30:23.402
The night Ariel Peterson
went missing.

30:23.698 --> 30:26.280
[ Crickets chirping ]

30:27.076 --> 30:30.568
Me and Trent, we worked
an 18-hour shift.

30:33.040 --> 30:35.292
It was a long, brutal day.

30:37.044 --> 30:40.878
I was wiped, so Trent
dropped me off at home.

30:41.882 --> 30:44.965
He said he'd take the ambulance
back and sign us both out.

30:49.724 --> 30:53.387
He told me he drove past Ariel
on the way to the hospital.

30:54.312 --> 30:55.768
She was drunk.

30:56.522 --> 30:59.810
She's been sick, and he knew
if he picked her up,

31:00.151 --> 31:02.483
his 18 hour shift
would turn into 22

31:02.486 --> 31:05.102
by the time they processed her
in the hospital.

31:08.075 --> 31:09.576
So he made sure she was okay...

31:11.871 --> 31:13.407
and left her to walk home.

31:13.831 --> 31:15.992
[ Crickets chirping ]

31:17.501 --> 31:19.958
Ask any paramedic,

31:19.962 --> 31:21.998
when you come across a kid
who's been drinking

31:22.006 --> 31:24.588
but who can still
make it home, you...

31:25.468 --> 31:27.129
You turn a blind eye.

31:28.095 --> 31:30.302
-Trent never imagined that...
-CHIEF: What?

31:30.598 --> 31:32.839
Ariel wouldn't make it home?
That she'd just disappear?

31:33.601 --> 31:34.841
No.

31:35.436 --> 31:37.802
CAM: You've known this
for five years, June.

31:39.398 --> 31:40.934
Never thought to tell us?

31:41.108 --> 31:42.518
I wanted to.

31:42.735 --> 31:44.020
But I...

31:45.321 --> 31:46.936
I promised Trent.

31:47.615 --> 31:49.355
This town would have never
forgiven him

31:49.367 --> 31:50.948
if I told you what happened.

31:53.120 --> 31:54.781
-So, that's it?
-Hmm.

31:54.789 --> 31:56.404
That's what you were
worried about?

31:56.832 --> 31:59.414
CHIEF: Did Trent say
where he saw Ariel last,

31:59.418 --> 32:01.704
what street was she on?

32:02.171 --> 32:03.331
Sheridan, I think.

32:04.423 --> 32:08.416
Just outside of town,
Sheridan and Market.

32:08.677 --> 32:10.884
All right,
I'm gonna go to the vaults,

32:10.888 --> 32:12.719
and I'm gonna pull all
the closed-circuit TV footage

32:12.723 --> 32:14.179
that I filed for that night.

32:14.183 --> 32:15.298
Anything on Sheridan Street,

32:15.309 --> 32:16.719
I'll go through with
a fine-tooth comb again.

32:16.727 --> 32:18.342
I'm sorry.

32:19.563 --> 32:22.179
-You're sorry?
-Cam... Cam you're not helping.

32:22.191 --> 32:24.307
-June, you're sorry?
-Cam...

32:24.568 --> 32:27.025
A 15-year-old girl went missing
that night, June!

32:27.405 --> 32:29.191
And you protected the piece
of shit who did that.

32:29.448 --> 32:30.654
You did!

32:39.625 --> 32:41.240
[ Buzzing ]

32:41.252 --> 32:42.332
[ Door unlocking ]

32:43.671 --> 32:46.788
[Chains jingling ]

33:10.072 --> 33:13.109
-Mr. Winston, thank you for...
-[ Door closing ]

33:13.117 --> 33:14.197
...agreeing to meet with me.

33:14.785 --> 33:16.821
As Sarah told you, I work
for the Waterbury Bulletin,

33:16.829 --> 33:18.114
and I think...

33:18.122 --> 33:22.240
you would provide invaluable
insight to this story.

33:28.716 --> 33:30.581
Okay, right.

33:41.562 --> 33:43.393
Can I ask you
why you want that?

33:46.650 --> 33:48.732
How much does Sarah know?

33:50.196 --> 33:51.151
Sorry.

33:51.447 --> 33:54.109
How much does Sarah know?

33:56.202 --> 33:58.659
About me being here? She gave me
your conditions. That's...

33:58.662 --> 34:01.779
How much does Sarah know
about you?

34:04.001 --> 34:05.866
Not sure I follow.

34:05.878 --> 34:08.494
I'm the one here to interview
you, not the other way around.

34:09.840 --> 34:12.707
[ Chains moving ]

34:12.718 --> 34:14.674
Sarah might've told you,

34:14.678 --> 34:17.715
I don't always read the letters
that are sent to me.

34:20.643 --> 34:22.884
But I did keep them.

34:23.229 --> 34:25.515
And I got a great memory...

34:26.649 --> 34:28.264
...for names.

34:33.322 --> 34:37.406
So again, Dylan.
How much does Sarah know?

34:44.166 --> 34:46.031
I told you I went
through all this footage,

34:46.043 --> 34:47.328
and I didn't find anything.

34:50.089 --> 34:52.330
Look, top left-hand corner.

34:56.053 --> 34:59.090
There.
That's Trent's ambulance.

35:07.648 --> 35:09.513
Now, watch closely.

35:10.609 --> 35:12.395
She's still there.

35:13.821 --> 35:15.311
Can you zoom in on this?
Blow it up?

35:15.614 --> 35:17.855
No, not on this.
But that's the intersection.

35:22.079 --> 35:23.910
[ Phone ringing distantly ]

35:24.498 --> 35:25.362
Shit.

35:26.208 --> 35:27.493
Yeah.

35:27.668 --> 35:29.374
She got in the car.

35:29.962 --> 35:32.078
Now, I don't have plates, but...

35:32.423 --> 35:34.038
It's a start.

35:45.102 --> 35:47.058
[ Birds chirping ]

35:48.522 --> 35:51.810
McBrides have always been
a troubled family.

35:52.860 --> 35:54.725
You know, I worked with Trent.

35:55.821 --> 35:57.777
I was his youth group leader.

35:58.282 --> 36:00.568
I tried and,
to some... extent,

36:00.576 --> 36:02.282
succeeded in putting him
on the right path.

36:02.453 --> 36:03.613
You're being sentimental.

36:03.912 --> 36:06.039
Of course,
I'm being sentimental.

36:06.373 --> 36:08.705
For Christ's sake...

36:10.127 --> 36:12.163
-Sometimes, Tom...
-What?

36:13.672 --> 36:16.129
Sometimes I forget
you're a Christian.

36:17.426 --> 36:18.711
[ Moving chains ]

36:18.969 --> 36:19.799
Yeah.

36:29.480 --> 36:33.519
"God is jealous,
and the Lord revengeth;

36:34.693 --> 36:38.811
The Lord revengeth,
and is furious;

36:38.822 --> 36:41.859
the Lord will take vengeance
on His adversaries,

36:41.867 --> 36:46.076
and He reserveth wrath
for His enemies."

36:46.080 --> 36:49.038
[ Moving chains ]

36:50.668 --> 36:53.910
It's not about turning off
your emotions, Alan.

36:54.463 --> 36:56.124
Grieve for them.

36:57.549 --> 37:00.416
Pray for them.
[ Moving chains ]

37:00.427 --> 37:02.884
But let that bolster
and strengthen your faith,

37:03.222 --> 37:04.928
rather than diminish it.

37:05.683 --> 37:08.345
God's work is being done.

37:10.604 --> 37:12.390
Open your Bible.

37:13.649 --> 37:15.230
Which Scripture would you
have me...?

37:15.567 --> 37:17.273
Just open it.

37:22.825 --> 37:24.486
Now you don't owe me anything.

37:25.035 --> 37:28.198
But if you revere the truth,
the way you claim to,

37:29.498 --> 37:31.284
you'll do this for me.

37:38.590 --> 37:40.581
None of you are safe!

37:43.011 --> 37:44.751
Your secrets!

37:45.431 --> 37:48.093
And your lies!
He sees them.

37:48.475 --> 37:51.387
And He exposes them,
and they lie there...

37:52.104 --> 37:55.722
grunting in the sun,
stinking to high heaven.

37:55.899 --> 37:59.733
You repent now,
or you will join them in Hell!

38:00.904 --> 38:02.895
Verna McBride!

38:02.906 --> 38:04.407
Can't walk.

38:04.616 --> 38:05.651
Can't touch.

38:07.035 --> 38:13.747
Justin Faysal, the rat.
In life and in death.

38:14.418 --> 38:17.455
Okay, Heather,
you need to stop, okay?

38:17.463 --> 38:20.876
Brenda Merritt, like Sisyphus!

38:21.258 --> 38:23.840
She just keeps rolling
that rock.

38:24.178 --> 38:27.011
Up the hill, into the water.

38:27.181 --> 38:28.341
[Giggling ]

38:28.348 --> 38:33.092
Trent McBride, that snake!

38:34.980 --> 38:37.187
If there is a God,

38:37.191 --> 38:41.150
I pray you let that snake devour
its own tail!

38:41.445 --> 38:43.982
And then start all over again!

38:44.198 --> 38:46.314
Until the end of time!

38:48.118 --> 38:49.449
Why?

38:50.037 --> 38:53.074
Why did you have to leave
Ariel behind?

38:55.000 --> 38:58.163
It would have taken...
five minutes.

38:58.712 --> 39:00.623
Five minutes.

39:00.631 --> 39:03.873
All you had to... stop
and to pick up my baby!

39:05.594 --> 39:08.006
And then bring her
home to me!

39:09.181 --> 39:10.512
[ Sobbing ]

39:12.059 --> 39:14.391
You would be here
with me instead!

39:14.394 --> 39:16.100
Oh, my God!

39:17.648 --> 39:19.354
[ Screaming ]

39:21.610 --> 39:24.977
If I could go back,
I'd take her place.

39:25.405 --> 39:26.781
I would.

39:27.533 --> 39:29.273
[ Sobbing ]

39:36.124 --> 39:38.501
What are you looking for
exactly?

39:39.002 --> 39:42.460
Well, Sheridan and Market
are north of here.

39:42.840 --> 39:44.796
So a vehicle would pass
by here south

39:44.800 --> 39:47.086
heading towards the hospital,
right?

39:48.011 --> 39:50.297
Probably.
It's the most direct route.

39:52.266 --> 39:54.973
Why did you have CCTV installed
outside the paper, anyway?

39:55.561 --> 39:57.927
You make more enemies than
friends in this line of work.

39:58.105 --> 39:59.561
Especially in a small town.

40:02.192 --> 40:03.147
Shit.

40:03.443 --> 40:04.603
What?

40:06.071 --> 40:09.655
That lying bitch
was with Trent that night.

40:10.492 --> 40:12.198
She was.

40:12.411 --> 40:14.367
That means she's next.

40:20.168 --> 40:22.079
You should know this will be
in the paper tomorrow,

40:22.087 --> 40:24.043
and on our site, as soon
as the story is written.

40:24.047 --> 40:26.709
Look, Alison, I know that you
have a business to run,

40:26.717 --> 40:27.832
but this is evidence.

40:27.843 --> 40:30.255
Which I gave you. Now
I'd like my tablet back, please.

40:30.512 --> 40:32.673
We're also talking about the
wife of one of my officers here.

40:34.182 --> 40:37.219
-He's got a point.
-No, actually, he doesn't.

40:37.644 --> 40:39.851
Okay, start downtown,
you find June Henry,

40:39.855 --> 40:41.686
you bring her back here,
you put her in Interview 1.

40:41.690 --> 40:43.021
Make sure she doesn't
talk to anybody,

40:43.025 --> 40:45.141
and you stay with her
until I get back.

40:46.028 --> 40:47.268
What's goin' on?

40:48.405 --> 40:49.520
[ Sighs ]

40:49.531 --> 40:50.941
It's June.

40:51.408 --> 40:52.648
What the hell's going on, Chief?

40:52.659 --> 40:55.241
She was in the ambulance
that night with Trent McBride.

40:55.245 --> 40:57.657
Her life is in danger,
so I'm bringing her in.

40:57.664 --> 40:58.915
But you've got her, right?
She's comin' in?

40:59.207 --> 41:00.367
I've got our guys
picking her up.

41:00.375 --> 41:02.866
Listen, Cam, I'm gonna need you
to sit this one out.

41:03.503 --> 41:05.755
JUNE: Hey, it's June.
Leave a message.

41:05.923 --> 41:09.290
June, it's me. Just call me
when you get this message.

41:10.135 --> 41:12.968
-Try her at work.
-It's her day off!

41:12.971 --> 41:13.926
All right, listen Cam.

41:13.931 --> 41:15.796
Her not answering her phone
doesn't mean anything.

41:15.807 --> 41:16.967
Maybe she didn't hear
the ringer,

41:16.975 --> 41:18.886
but I'll stop by your house
and see if she's there.

41:18.894 --> 41:20.600
Okay, yeah.
Well, I'm comin' with you.

41:20.771 --> 41:23.433
No, you're not. Just... go for a
coffee with Sarah or something.

41:23.607 --> 41:24.847
Yeah, you know, absolut...

41:25.025 --> 41:27.892
-I'm coming with you.
-No, you're not.

41:27.903 --> 41:30.690
You're too close to this.
I need the keys to your house.

41:31.615 --> 41:33.526
Give me the keys
to your house, Cam.

41:36.161 --> 41:37.776
[ Keys jingling ]

41:39.873 --> 41:40.988
All right, everyone, listen up.

41:40.999 --> 41:43.490
I want every available officer
to search downtown.

41:43.502 --> 41:45.743
You find June Henry, and you
bring her back here right away.

41:45.754 --> 41:47.039
Cam, you leave
your cell phone on,

41:47.047 --> 41:48.662
and I'll call you the minute
I know anything.

41:48.674 --> 41:51.040
Kelly, grab my gun belt!
Let's go!

41:52.928 --> 41:54.213
Come on.

41:55.180 --> 41:56.761
SARAH: Let's get coffee.

42:02.896 --> 42:05.012
Thank God for you, Sarah.

42:05.023 --> 42:08.060
If you hadn't, uh,
looked for that footage...

42:08.527 --> 42:10.893
You're so loyal, Cam, you know?

42:11.905 --> 42:13.611
It's one of the things
I love most about you,

42:13.615 --> 42:16.857
but this keeps happening
over and over.

42:18.662 --> 42:21.244
That's Chief Vaughn, okay?
He's just overwhelmed.

42:21.456 --> 42:24.539
He's incompetent...
and dangerous.

42:28.338 --> 42:29.544
June wasn't home.

42:29.548 --> 42:31.084
If she was home, they would
have called by now.

42:31.091 --> 42:32.752
No. That doesn't mean anything.

42:32.759 --> 42:34.670
It's her day off.
She could be anywhere.

42:35.971 --> 42:37.802
Uh, I just can't sit here
and wait.

42:38.432 --> 42:39.968
For once, Vaughn, he's right.

42:39.975 --> 42:42.057
That is exactly
what you need to do.

42:43.186 --> 42:44.801
Could you do that, Sarah?

42:44.813 --> 42:46.929
Could you just sit here and wait
if that was happening to Dylan?

42:48.984 --> 42:51.191
No, no.
Anyone can reach me.

42:51.820 --> 42:53.310
But I gotta join the search.

43:20.265 --> 43:21.596
June?

43:25.854 --> 43:27.594
June, are you here?

43:42.079 --> 43:43.285
June?

43:48.376 --> 43:50.162
June, it's Vaughn.

44:09.606 --> 44:10.766
June?

44:26.081 --> 44:27.742
Put your hands up!
Right now!

44:46.768 --> 44:48.349
This is Chief Vaughn.

44:48.520 --> 44:51.136
I'm gonna need forensics
over at the Henry household.

44:51.690 --> 44:53.601
We got ourselves
a crime scene now.

44:54.401 --> 44:56.437
I'm gonna rejoin the search
for June.

44:57.112 --> 44:58.477
DISPATCHER:
...sending units now.

44:58.655 --> 45:00.191
Son of a bitch.

45:01.575 --> 45:03.065
Please, Lord.

45:03.493 --> 45:05.950
Bring Ariel back to her mother...

45:06.496 --> 45:09.579
...end their suffering
for our mistake.

45:09.583 --> 45:12.040
Please, God, I beg you.
I would do any...

45:12.043 --> 45:13.624
[ Doors swing open ]

45:24.890 --> 45:26.755
I knew you'd come for me.

45:33.190 --> 45:35.306
[ Muffled screaming ]

46:00.467 --> 46:02.003
Where the hell have you been?

46:04.179 --> 46:05.760
You leave work, you don't
tell me where you're going.

46:06.014 --> 46:07.424
You don't answer your phone.

46:07.432 --> 46:09.593
I was out hunting a story.

46:09.601 --> 46:11.432
But if you prefer me sitting
at my desk from 9 to 5,

46:11.436 --> 46:12.346
we can have that.

46:12.354 --> 46:14.094
I'm asking
for some common courtesy.

46:14.105 --> 46:16.141
Yeah, and I'm asking
for the same.

46:16.316 --> 46:18.352
'Cause I don't really appreciate
being made to feel

46:18.360 --> 46:19.600
like a teenager cutting class.

46:24.407 --> 46:26.068
I met with Tom Winston.

46:30.288 --> 46:31.368
Sarah didn't tell me.

46:31.373 --> 46:33.159
You called Sarah?
Are you kidding me?

46:33.375 --> 46:35.411
No, she came in.

46:35.585 --> 46:38.167
With an actual lead
on an actual story.

46:38.421 --> 46:39.581
One that I wanted you to write,

46:39.589 --> 46:41.125
but instead I did my own
shit job of it

46:41.132 --> 46:42.417
because you wouldn't
answer your phone.

46:42.425 --> 46:44.256
Okay, I'm here.
What is it?

46:46.054 --> 46:49.171
When I hired you,
I took a chance.

46:49.182 --> 46:50.968
Yeah, you'd written
for some major publications.

46:50.976 --> 46:54.969
But you have never
run a paper. Okay?

46:55.272 --> 46:57.137
I hope you don't forget that.

46:58.108 --> 47:01.566
Send me what you got on it.
Get right on it.

47:16.418 --> 47:18.955
[ Crickets chirping ]

47:32.934 --> 47:35.095
Alan. Hey.

47:35.353 --> 47:37.890
I heard you found June's purse
in your church.

47:38.440 --> 47:39.520
Yes.

47:39.524 --> 47:41.355
Any word on June herself?

47:42.193 --> 47:43.478
How's he doing?

47:44.821 --> 47:46.152
I don't know.

47:47.032 --> 47:50.195
-Sarah, I should...
-Oh, yes, of course. I'm sorry.

47:50.452 --> 47:52.784
[ Crickets chirping ]

48:01.546 --> 48:02.535
Can I sit?

48:02.756 --> 48:05.247
[ Crickets continue chirping ]

48:12.640 --> 48:15.052
Why did you have to come back
to Waterbury, Sarah?

48:18.313 --> 48:20.144
-I...
-No.

48:21.649 --> 48:23.685
It's just this...

48:24.903 --> 48:26.609
...this darkness.

48:27.697 --> 48:29.437
It follows you everywhere.

48:30.367 --> 48:32.608
Your whole life.

48:34.871 --> 48:36.907
Now, it's latched onto us.

48:41.503 --> 48:43.118
Okay...

48:45.799 --> 48:48.040
[ Crickets chirping ]

48:54.682 --> 48:55.432
[ Door closing ]

48:56.518 --> 48:58.429
[ Birds chirping ]

49:27.841 --> 49:29.877
[ Labored breathing ]

49:54.409 --> 49:57.071
[ Rodent squeaking ]
